<h2>A2: The /proc/ccs interface</h2>

<h3><a name="audit">/proc/ccs/audit</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface contains the audit log. The reader process returns immediately if no granted log exists. To wait until an audit log is generated, use select(2) for readability.</p>

<p>This interface is dependent on how the profiles have been configured in "/proc/ccs/profile". The following profile options affect it:</p>
<ul>
<li>grant_log</li>
<li>reject_log</li>
<li>max_audit_log</li>
</ul>

<h3><a name="domain_policy">/proc/ccs/domain_policy</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface contains the policy that is defined for each domain. Any lines starting with "&lt;kernel&gt;" indicate the start of a new block of access permissions.</p>

<p>The associated configuration file is "/etc/ccs/domain_policy.conf".</p>

<h3><a name="exception_policy">/proc/ccs/exception_policy</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface contains the exception policy. Each line is an individual entry.</p>

<p>The associated configuration file is "/etc/ccs/exception_policy.conf".</p>

<h3><a name="manager">/proc/ccs/manager</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface contains a list of either domains or full pathnames that have been given permission to write to the "/proc/ccs" interface.</p>

<p>The associated configuration file is "/etc/ccs/manager.conf".</p>

<pre class="command">
# cat /proc/ccs/manager
</pre>

<pre class="output">
/usr/sbin/ccs-loadpolicy
/usr/sbin/ccs-editpolicy
/usr/sbin/ccs-setlevel
/usr/sbin/ccs-setprofile
/usr/sbin/ccs-queryd
</pre>

<h3><a name="meminfo">/proc/ccs/meminfo</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface shows the memory usage of TOMOYO Linux in bytes.</p>

<pre class="command">
# cat /proc/ccs/meminfo
</pre>

<pre class="output">
Policy:          377376
Audit logs:           0
Query lists:          0
Total:           377376
</pre>

<ul>
<li><strong>Policy</strong> shows the memory used for holding access permissions.</li>
<li><strong>Audit logs</strong> shows the memory used for holding audit logs.</li>
<li><strong>Query lists</strong> shows the memory used while running the userspace tool "/usr/sbin/ccs-queryd".</li>
<li><strong>Total</strong> shows the total memory used.</li>
</ul>

<h3><a name="profile">/proc/ccs/profile</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface contains the profile configuration.</p>

<p>The associated configuration file is "/etc/ccs/profile.conf".</p>

<h3><a name="query">/proc/ccs/query</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface is used to grant or reject individual access requests that occur within domains in "Enforcing Mode".</p>

<p>This interface is used primarily by the userspace tool <a href="section-1.html.en#ccs-queryd">ccs-queryd</a>.</p>

<h3><a name="self_domain">/proc/ccs/self_domain</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface shows the domain of the caller process.</p>

<h3><a name="stat">/proc/ccs/stat</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface contains information about policy violations and memory usage.</p>

<pre class="command">
# cat /proc/ccs/stat
</pre>

<pre class="output">
Policy update:                               172 (Last: 2011/02/03 18:03:01)
Policy violation in learning mode:             0
Policy violation in permissive mode:           0
Policy violation in enforcing mode:            0
Memory used by policy:                     41792
Memory used by audit log:                 159328
Memory used by query message:                  0
Total memory used:                        201120
</pre>

<ul>
<li><strong>Policy update</strong> shows the total number of domains and the last time that policy was updated.</li>
<li><strong>Policy violation in learning mode</strong> shows the total number of policy violations that have occurred in domains set to "Learning Mode".</li>
<li><strong>Policy violation in permissive mode</strong> shows the total number of policy violations that have occurred in domains set to "Permissive Mode".</li>
<li><strong>Policy violation in enforcing mode</strong> shows the total number of policy violations that have occurred in domains set to "Enforcing Mode".</li>
</ul>

<h3><a name="version">/proc/ccs/version</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface contains the currently running version of TOMOYO Linux.</p>

<h3><a name=".domain_status">/proc/ccs/.domain_status</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface contains a list of domain names and profile numbers currently defined in domain policy.</p>

<p>This is used primarily by the userspace tool <a href="section-1.html.en#ccs-setprofile">ccs-setprofile</a>.</p>

<h3><a name=".execute_handler">/proc/ccs/.execute_handler</a></h3>

<p>This read-only interface contains information regarding the execute handler.</p>

<h3><a name=".process_status">/proc/ccs/.process_status</a></h3>

<p>This read/write interface contains a list of domain names and profile numbers that the currently running process belongs to.</p>

<p>This interface is used primarily by the userspace tool <a href="section-1.html.en#ccs-pstree">ccs-pstree</a>.</p>

